, 104].\n-106 <= Node.val <= 106\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\n# Definition for singly-linked list.\n# class ListNode:\n#     def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):\n#         self.val = val\n#         self.next = next\nclass Solution:\n    def oddEvenList(self, head: Optional[ListNode]) -> Optional[ListNode]:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\n# Definition for singly-linked list.\n# class ListNode:\n#     def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):\n#         self.val = val\n#         self.next = next\nclass Solution:\n    def oddEvenList(self, head: Optional[ListNode]) -> Optional[ListNode]:\n        if not head or not head.next or not head.next.next:\n            return head\n        \n        # Initialize pointers for odd and even nodes\n        odd_head = head\n        even_head = head.next\n        odd = odd_head\n        even = even_head\n        \n        # Iterate through the list, rearranging nodes\n        while even and even.next:\n            odd.next = even.next\n            odd = odd.next\n            even.next = odd.next\n            even = even.next\n        \n        # Connect the end of odd list to the head of even list\n        odd.next = even_head\n        \n        return odd_head\n```\n\nThis solution maintains the relative order of nodes with odd and even indices while ensuring O(1) extra space complexity and O(n) time complexity. The key idea is to rearrange the pointers in place, separating odd and even indexed nodes and then joining them at the end.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}